<subSubSection box="[151,404,1805,1831]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,730,1765,1831]" box="[151,404,1805,1831]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">(Barsim grasshopper)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="21" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1885,2031]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,281,1885,1911]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The species is generally slender, sometimes with somewhat shortened tegmina. The hind legs are long and slender. It can be distinguished by its characteristic hind tibiae, blue in proximal half with one or two pale bands and bright red distally, as also are the tarsi and by male cercus narrow, weakly compressed with acute apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,151,698]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,314,151,177]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Habitats:</emphasis>
It is ambivorous and predominantly a grassland species. It is also found in cultivated ground and in abondoned farmland. This species rarely occurs in this area. Only few specimens were collected from alfalfa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
